            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Leo Kaur\u2019s name often prompts a question, one he answers with quiet pride. The son of a Punjabi Sikh mother, a fiercely independent nurse, and a white an-d-father from Oregon, a gentle carpenter, Leo was raised in a Portland suburb where two cultures coexisted under one roof. When he turned 18, he legally took his mother's surname, Kaur, a tribute to her strength and a conscious choice to honor a lineage he felt deeply connected to, even if he didn't share her faith.\n\nHis intellectual curiosity led him to UC Santa Cruz, where he pursued a degree in Cognitive Science. He was fascinated by the \"why\" behind human choices\u2014the invisible architecture of thought that dictates our interaction with the world. This academic passion found a practical, lucrative outlet in the Bay Area\u2019s tech boom. He landed an internship, which quickly converted into a full-time User Experience Researcher position at a management consulting firm in SoMa. Now, he spends his days translating user frustrations and desires into actionable data, a role he finds both analytical and deeply empathetic.\n\nA key turning point was a project focused on digital accessibility for the visually impaired. Witnessing firsthand how thoughtful design could radically improve someone's independence gave his career a profound sense of purpose beyond just optimizing interfaces. He realized his work could be a form of advocacy.\n\nToday, Leo lives a quintessentially San Francisco life. His 2.8-mile bicycle commute from his shared apartment in the Mission is a daily ritual, a whirlwind of murals, traffic, and the scent of bakeries that grounds him in the city's vibrant chaos. His $135,000 income affords him a comfortable life, though he remains frugal, preferring to spend on experiences over possessions. Evenings are for bouldering at Dogpatch Boulders with friends or exploring the city\u2019s endless culinary scene.\n\nWhile content, Leo aspires for more. He dreams of one day leading a research team focused on ethical AI and digital wellness, ensuring technology serves humanity, not the other way around. He also nurtures a quiet hope to travel to Punjab, to walk the lands his mother described and connect with a part of his identity he has so far only known through stories."
